1 the required lethal substances substances, if any, and certify the fact of the execution. If a licensed
2 physician is not present at the execution, then a licensed physician shall be present on the
3 premises and available to examine the body after the execution and pronounce the person dead.
4 Four respectable citizens, two members of the victim's family, the counsel and any relatives of
5 such person, convict or felon and a minister or member of the clergy or religious leader of the
6 person's choosing may be present if they so desire. The identities, including the names, residential
7 addresses, residential telephone numbers, and social security numbers, of witnesses or persons
8 designated to carry out the execution shall be confidential and exempted from Chapter 132 of the
9 General Statutes and are not subject to discovery or introduction as evidence in any proceeding.
10 The Senior Resident Superior Court Judge for Wake County may order disclosure of names made
11 confidential by this section after making findings that support a conclusion that disclosure is
12 necessary to a proper administration of justice.
13 For purposes of this section, a "medical professional other than a physician" means a
14 physician assistant, nurse practitioner, registered nurse, emergency medical technician, or
15 emergency medical technician-paramedic who is licensed or credentialed by the licensing board,
16 agency, or organization responsible for licensing or credentialing that profession."
17 SECTION 6.5.(e) G.S. 7A-27 reads as rewritten:
18 "§ 7A-27. Appeals of right from the courts of the trial divisions.
19 (a) Appeal lies of right directly to the Supreme Court in any of the following cases:
20 (1) All cases in which the defendant is convicted of murder in the first degree and
21 the judgment of the superior court includes a sentence of death.
22 (2) From any final judgment in a case designated as a mandatory complex
23 business case pursuant to G.S. 7A-45.4 or designated as a discretionary
24 complex business case pursuant to Rule 2.1 of the General Rules of Practice
25 for the Superior and District Courts.
26 (3) From any interlocutory order of a Business Court Judge that does any of the
27 following:
28 a. Affects a substantial right.
29 b. In effect determines the action and prevents a judgment from which an
30 appeal might be taken.
31 c. Discontinues the action.
32 d. Grants or refuses a new trial.
33 (4) Any trial court's decision regarding class action certification under G.S. 1A-1,
34 Rule 23.
35 (5) Repealed by Session Laws 2021-18, s. 1, effective July 1, 2021, and applicable
36 to appeals filed on or after that date.
37 (6) In all cases where a defendant has challenged a method of execution under
38 G.S. 15-188, and a trial court has declared the method unconstitutional.
39 …."
40 SECTION 6.5.(f) G.S. 150B-1(d) is amended by adding a new subdivision to read:
41 "(35) The Department of Adult Correction, with respect to the establishment and
42 administration of any method of execution pursuant to G.S. 15-188."".

